# Hermes — Personal AI Assistant Experiment

> An ongoing experimentation project exploring persistent AI assistant workflows,
> skill-based automation, and practical agentic system design.

---

## Overview

This project is a practical exploration of what it takes to run a **persistent, personalised AI assistant** on personal infrastructure — not as a commercial product, but as a learning exercise in agentic system design, operational AI thinking, and real-world workflow automation.

The assistant runs on a self-hosted VPS using [Hermes Agent](https://hermes-agent.nousresearch.com/) (Nous Research, MIT licence) with Anthropic's Claude as the underlying model. Interaction happens entirely through Telegram, making it accessible from any device without a dedicated frontend.

This is not a demo. It runs continuously, handles real tasks, and is iterated on weekly.

---

## Project Goal

To understand — through hands-on experimentation — how a persistent AI assistant can:

- Reduce cognitive overhead in everyday planning (meals, shopping, schedules)
- Filter information noise (market updates, email newsletters, deal alerts)
- Integrate with external services (calendars, task managers, data APIs)
- Scale in capability through composable skills and MCP integrations
- Operate reliably on modest infrastructure without managed cloud services

The working hypothesis: **a well-configured, persistent agent with good memory and targeted skills outperforms a general-purpose chatbot for personal workflow automation** — even on lightweight hardware.

