## High-Level Architecture

```
┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│  Users (Telegram)                               │
│  ─ Primary user (mobile + desktop)             │
│  ─ Secondary user (mobile, WhatsApp planned)   │
└─────────────────────┬───────────────────────────┘
                      │
┌─────────────────────▼───────────────────────────┐
│  Hermes Gateway (Docker, self-hosted VPS)       │
│                                                  │
│  ┌──────────────────────────────────────────┐   │
│  │  Agent                                   │   │
│  │  Model: Claude Sonnet 4.6 (Anthropic)   │   │
│  │  Memory: Honcho + FTS5 (persistent)      │   │
│  │  Skills: custom + bundled                │   │
│  └──────────────────────────────────────────┘   │
└─────────────────────┬───────────────────────────┘
                      │
┌─────────────────────▼───────────────────────────┐
│  Integrations                                    │
│  ─ Todoist REST API (task/list management)      │
│  ─ Google Workspace (Calendar, Gmail) [planned] │
│  ─ MCP servers (crypto data, weather) [planned] │
│  ─ Internal cron job outputs [read-only]        │
└─────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
```

**Key design decisions:**

- **Single agent, multiple tools** — one persistent assistant routes to skills and APIs rather than spawning separate bots per domain
- **Memory over re-prompting** — the agent accumulates facts about preferences, habits, and context across sessions via a structured memory layer
- **Read-only by default** — integrations that touch external systems (trading outputs, email) default to read-only access until explicit write permissions are added

