## Operational Considerations

**Cost management**

Running Claude Sonnet 4.6 via the Anthropic API at typical personal usage (~20–40 messages/day including agent tool calls) costs roughly $10–20/month. Early testing with Opus 4.7 ran significantly higher due to a tokenizer change that increased effective token usage by ~35% for the same input length.

Practical cost controls in use:
- Sonnet 4.6 as default (not Opus)
- Compressed SOUL.md persona file to reduce per-message system prompt overhead
- Instructed the agent to respond concisely and avoid unnecessary preamble
- Context compression enabled at 50% threshold (built into Hermes)
- Separate API key per workload for granular cost tracking

**Coexistence with existing automation**

The VPS also runs a separate trading analysis script on a cron schedule. The two systems are isolated by design — the assistant has no write access to the trading process and currently has no read access either. Future integration will be read-only: the assistant will summarise outputs from log files, not interact with the trading logic directly.

**Known limitations**

During setup, a bug was identified in Hermes (issue [#26596](https://github.com/NousResearch/hermes-agent/issues/26596)) where `SOUL.md` persona files are not reliably loaded in gateway mode. The workaround observed in practice: the persistent memory layer (`USER.md`) accumulates persona-relevant facts over time from conversations, effectively substituting for the static persona file in steady-state usage. The agent's behaviour converges toward the intended persona within a few sessions without requiring a code-level fix.

This kind of **"debug in production, document the gap, find the workaround"** cycle is a core part of what makes this project useful as a learning exercise.

