## Key Learnings

**On persistent memory vs. static prompts**

A static system prompt (SOUL.md) is fragile — it has to be right from day one and doesn't adapt. A memory layer that accumulates facts from real conversations is more robust. The agent corrects its own misunderstandings (e.g. inferring the correct legal name structure for household members from conversational context) without being explicitly programmed to do so.

**On skill design**

Skills work best when they are narrow and opinionated. A meal planner skill that knows the household's pantry baseline, portion conventions, and dietary preferences produces far better output than a generic "plan meals" prompt. The effort of writing a good skill pays back immediately and compounds over time.

**On cost vs. capability**

Frontier models are not always necessary. For everyday assistant tasks — planning, summarising, formatting, routing — a mid-tier model (Sonnet) is indistinguishable from a frontier model (Opus) in practice, at 40% lower cost. The cases where Opus is worth it are narrow: complex multi-step reasoning, code generation, or novel problem-solving.

**On agentic system design**

The most useful framing for this project has been: **the agent is an orchestration layer, not a capability layer**. It does not need to know how to book a flight — it needs to know when to call a tool that books flights. Keeping this separation clean makes the system easier to extend, easier to debug, and cheaper to run.

**On adoption and validation**

The critical unknown for personal automation is whether a second person (the other household member) will actually use it. The system is technically functional, but adoption depends on friction — and friction is determined by interface choice, response quality, and whether the agent saves more time than it costs to interact with. This is being treated as a product problem, not a technical one.

